pable due to a few insults is... well... illogical.  This one annoys me.<br><br>&quot;Well, I don't care if you just single-handedly disproved both Enstein and the whole of Quantum Physics while presenting a flawless alternative way of viewing reality to which all natural laws obey and follow... you just called me a poopy-head,  thereby nullifying your argument with an ad hominum remark.&quot;<br><br>Nor does it refer to arguements were the person or the logic of their arguement IS the issue at hand and the remarks were directed, not hurt the person, but to address the discussion and/or come to a logical conclusion about that person which is relivant to the issue.  (See: 90% of the threads in this forum in which the term Ad hominem is used) <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ukreelosthehunter.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Kreelos the Hunter</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 188<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(8/12/02 2:54:34 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1180.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_supermad.gif" align=absmiddle>  I would say</span><hr size=1> &quot;Isn't this a logical fallicy of it's own? An appeal to authority or some such? I am &quot;expert&quot; on this subject, therefore I am to be believed. Well, sorry, but the 'experts' on geography back in 1312 'knew' the world to be flat. Sorry, I just see the image of a logic teacher using a logical fallicy in an attempt to show the class that he knows his logic to be funny. &quot;<br><br>Comparing Geography, an empirical science, with Philosophy, a social science, would be a logical fallacy. Philosophical definitions are set by philosophers.  The shape of the world is observed empiric